# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# What this repo carries: the manual, and the SOURCE of the films — scripts,
# Remotion projects, configs. What it does not carry: the media. Recordings,
# renders, and the derived asset pool are large, and every one of them can be
# rebuilt from something (with one exception, noted below).
#
# Rule of thumb: if a human wrote it, it's tracked. If a machine emitted it,
# it isn't.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# The raw 4K screen captures. Large, and the repo does not need them: the frames
# used as figures are already extracted into manual_assets/, and the clips the
# films actually cut from are derived into 2_EDITS/assets/video-seekable/.
1_SCREEN_RECORDINGS/

# ── 2_EDITS — track what a film is built FROM, not what it is built OUT OF ──

# Dependencies. Hoisted to 2_EDITS/node_modules by the npm workspace, but npm also
# writes per-project trees for platform-specific binaries.
node_modules/

# Rendered films. Every project emits into out/; regenerate with `npm run build`
# in that project.
out/

# The derived asset pool (~235M): re-encoded seekable clips, extracted stills, and
# the ElevenLabs voiceover.
#
# ⚠️ Not all of this is free to rebuild. The clips and stills are ffmpeg one-liners
# (recipes are in each project's README), but assets/audio/ is SYNTHESIZED VOICEOVER
# and re-generating it costs ElevenLabs credits — and a re-synthesis will not be
# sample-identical, so every scene length derived from it (see each project's
# timeline.ts) would need re-measuring. If you hand this repo to someone who has to
# rebuild the films, ship assets/ alongside it or they will be re-recording the VO.
2_EDITS/assets/

# The same media again, copied. The Remotion projects reach the asset pool through a
# SYMLINK at public/assets -> ../../../assets, but the two older revideo projects
# (L1_VersionA, L1_VersionB) hold real copies there instead — 32M of duplicated mp4
# and mp3. Ignore the copies.
#
# The trailing slash is doing real work: it matches directories only, and git records
# a symlink as a blob rather than a directory. So the revideo copies are ignored while
# the Remotion symlinks stay tracked — which is what we want, because those symlinks
# are how each project finds its footage.
**/public/assets/

# Bundler / renderer caches
.remotion/

# HyperFrames scratch (L1_VersionA/B): thumbnail jpgs and decoded audio waveforms,
# rebuilt on demand from the assets they describe.
.thumbnails/
.waveform-cache/

# Scratch notes
Untitled.md

# macOS
.DS_Store
._*
.Spotlight-V100
.Trashes

# Python
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
.venv/
venv/

# Editors
.idea/
.vscode/
*.swp

# NOTE: docs/ is deliberately NOT ignored. It holds the built site
# (index.html + the two PDFs) and is what GitHub Pages serves.
